I'm in Mayssa Mokalled's lab (https://www.mokalledlab.com/). I just transferred into the lab after my first professor left the university, so my picture and bio aren't on the lab website yet. We study spinal cord regeneration in zebrafish. Most of the lab focuses on cellular regeneration, but my focus is on functional recovery -- the fish's ability to swim with a non-paralyzed gait after the spinal cord reconnects. Hi Jonathan, decided to get a PhD for a couple of reasons: I believed I would have more career opportunities with one, and my dad kept saying that I would be "Dr. Nick" someday -- a joke that I took to heart. Whether you want to get a PhD depends on what you plan to do. Have you looked at job postings that you'd like to apply for someday? Do they require a PhD, or just four years of experience? It sounds like you may have some experience already, and certainly the MS in pharmacology should count for something depending on the job. I'd also recommend having a professional interview with a person who has a job that you think you would like to do. I talked with a data scientist about his job, and it was a helpful conversation for me. As for schools, since you have a background in pharmacology, I'd expect that you would want to do a PhD in bioinformatics/computational biology at a medical school. I don't know much about other schools, but here at Washington University in St Louis, there's a strong connection to the medical school and we even have our programs on the medical campus (MD/PhD students are common, and translational research is common). I'm sure University of Utah, St. Louis University, and any other campus with a hospital or medical program would be a good choice for you. Beyond that, talking to recruiters at schools to find out whether there's a good fit for you is helpful. I did that at a few schools before applying. I hope your plans go well!

-So for my role as a news analyst we work with what is called the learning loop which is essentially the phenomenon that as we work we refine our AI technologies and at the same our AI technologies help us refine our alerting for our clients. As you work with the AI tech, it develops a report understanding of human interaction and therefore can help you yield more alerts   -My work involves more day to day, short term productivity expectations as the object of my day is to create as many alerts and endorse them as possible   -I am working remotely, once we “go live” (aka the start of our shift) we work to endorse alerts and we are constantly on a Google hangout or slack call (usually muted with camera off unless we have any questions for the group). The main objective for my role is primarily the alerts   -The interview process was in three stages, nothing too serious everyone is pretty laid back and cool. A tip would be going into the interview very informed about current events, COVID, political events, etc. anything newsworthy and how their implications. Additionally, I would I highlight good communication skills and outside knowledge of media, news media, etc

CONTENT: Oh sure! I learned in school that the central dogma is DNA is read and transcribed into mRNA before being read and translated into proteins. The notion that there may be some additional modifications of mRNA is interesting to me because I learned about DNA modification and protein modification during and after translation, but my professors haven't discussed mRNA in detail.

Dear Maria,My name is Maria Misbach and I work with the Professional MBA (PMBA) program at the University of Utah, which is Utah's #1 ranked part-time MBA program for working professionals. Your background and goals seem like they might be a good fit for our program. Two of the most commonly asked questions we receive are: "How will an MBA help me?" and "Can I be successful in an MBA program without a business undergraduate or background?"As one of the most versatile graduate degrees out there, an MBA prepares students for advanced careers in any industry. An MBA can equip you to move into management, start your own business, change careers, or shift your career focus. It can train you to become a specialist in any number of business disciplines such as finance, marketing, operations, international business, and more.So how does the University of Utah Professional MBA program work for individuals that don't have a business background?First off, not having a business undergraduate degree or background will not hinder you in the admissions process or in your ability to succeed in the program. In fact, the majority of University of Utah PMBA students and alumni come from a non-business background, and our admissions committee looks favorably upon students that increase the educational and professional diversity of the class.Many business schools require prerequisites like accounting, statistics, or finance, but the PMBA program does not require any specific classes to apply. The admissions committee evaluates for quantitative skills by looking at previous coursework, GMAT/GRE score, job responsibilities, professional certifications, and more. All incoming PMBA students go through a program-sponsored MBA Math course prior to beginning classes. The online, self-paced lessons in finance, accounting, economics, statistics, and spreadsheets ensure that you feel prepared for the quantitative aspects of MBA core coursework before you even start.Teamwork is a huge focus in the PMBA program, and students from different backgrounds learn to rely on and learn from each other's strengths. As we build each team, special attention is paid to balancing the different quantitative and qualitative skill sets in each group. Ready to learn more? I invite you to download our latest program brochure by clicking on the "Download Brochure" link now. Alternatively, we invite you to connect with us by attending one of our upcoming admissions events or reaching out to one of our advisors at 801-581-6836 or PMBA@Utah.edu. We hope to hear from you soon. Best regards,Maria MisbachUniversity of UtahDavid Eccles School of BusinessProfessional MBA
